.SH NAME
sysopctl \- A custom Linux utility for managing system services and resources.

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B sysopctl
[\fB--help\fR] [\fB--version\fR] \fIcommand\fR [\fIoptions\fR] \fIarguments\fR

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B sysopctl
is a comprehensive tool designed to streamline the management of system services, processes, disk usage, and overall system health. It offers an intuitive interface for administrators to perform routine tasks with ease.

.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B service list
Displays a list of all running services on the system.

.TP
.B service start <service-name>
Starts the specified service if it is not already running.

.TP
.B service stop <service-name>
Stops the specified service if it is currently active.

.TP
.B system load
Shows the current system load, providing average CPU and system performance over time.

.TP
.B disk usage
Provides a detailed overview of disk space usage across all partitions.

.TP
.B process monitor
Enables real-time monitoring of active system processes.

.TP
.B logs analyze
Retrieves and summarizes critical log entries from recent system activities.

.TP
.B backup <path>
Initiates a backup of files from the specified directory to a designated backup location.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B --help
Displays a detailed help message with available commands and usage information.

.TP
.B --version
Displays the current version of \fBsysopctl\fR.

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B sysopctl service list
Outputs a list of currently running system services.

.TP
.B sysopctl service start apache2
Starts the Apache2 web server service.

.TP
.B sysopctl service stop apache2
Stops the Apache2 web server service.

.TP
.B sysopctl system load
Shows the system load averages for the last 1, 5, and 15 minutes.

.TP
.B sysopctl disk usage
Displays disk usage statistics for all mounted partitions.

.TP
.B sysopctl process monitor
Begins real-time monitoring of system processes and their resource consumption.

.TP
.B sysopctl logs analyze
Fetches and summarizes critical error logs from the system.

.TP
.B sysopctl backup /home/user
Initiates a backup of the contents of the \fB/home/user\fR directory.

